chapter.article:
Contracting Parties shall not:

directly or indirectly impose on goods from the other Party, covered by this Agreement, internal taxes or charges, in excess of corresponding taxes and charges imposed on similar goods of domestic production or on goods of third country origin;

apply in respect of import or export of goods, covered by this Agreement, any special limitations or requirements, which in similar situation shall not apply to like goods of domestic production or goods of third country origin;

apply in respect of warehousing, reloading, storage, transportation of goods that originating from the territory of the other Contracting Party, as well as of payments and payment transfers rules other than those applied in similar situations regarding goods of domestic production or goods of third country origin.

1. The Contracting Parties shall undertake not to apply quantitative restrictions or equivalent measures on export and (or) import on goods under this Agreement.

2. The quantitative restrictions referred to in paragraph 1 of this Article may be set under unilateral procedure within reasonable limits and for a strictly defined time only in cases of:

acute shortage of a given good on the domestic market - until the stabilization of the situation on the market;

acute balance of payments deficit - until the stabilization of the balance of payments;

in case if a good is imported into the territory of one of the Contracting Parties in such increased quantities and on such terms that cause or threaten to cause damage to domestic producers of like or directly competitive goods;

in order to take measures provided for in Article 4 of the present Agreement.

3. The quantitative restrictions referred to in paragraph 1 of the Article may also be set by mutual consent of the Parties and be included in the protocols referred to in paragraph 1 of Article 1 of the present Agreement.

4. The Contracting Party that applies quantitative restrictions in accordance with paragraph 2 of this Article shall, by the request of the other Contracting Party, provide necessary information about the reasons of introduction, forms and possible time of application of the referred to restrictions.

5. The Contracting Parties shall strive to resolve all the issues that arise from the introduction of the quantitative restrictions referred to in paragraph 2 of this Article through consultations.

6. When selecting the measures in compliance with this Article, the Contracting Parties shall give priority to those of them that produce the least negative impact on the achievement of the purposes of the present Agreement.

The Contracting Parties recognize the incompatibility with the purposes of the present Agreement of unfair business practices manifested, in particular, in the following:

concluding agreements between enterprises, and its unions, having by its aim to hinder or restrict competition or violate its terms on the territories of the Contracting Parties;

making actions by which one or several enterprises use their dominating status, restricting competition on the entire or a substantial part of the territories of the Contracting Parties.

Nothing in this Agreement shall not prevent the right of the Contracting Parties from taking, commonly recognized in international practice, measures, which it considers necessary for protecting their vital interests or which are undoubtedly necessary for compliance with international agreements to which they are or intend to become parties, if these measures relate to:

information affecting the interests of national defence;

trade in arms, munitions and military equipment;

research or production related to the defence needs;

supply of materials and equipment used in nuclear industry;

protection of public morality and public order;

protection of industrial and intellectual property;

gold, silver, and other precious metals and stones;

protection of human, animal and plant life.
